      text: 'I think what strikes me most about the current media landscape is the paradox at its heart: we have more information available to more people than at any point in human history, and yet there is a compelling case that the quality of public deliberation has deteriorated rather than improved. Not only is the sheer volume of information difficult to navigate — the structural incentives of the attention economy actively reward content that provokes emotional reaction over content that informs. Furthermore, the collapse of the advertising-supported local news model has created information deserts — communities with no significant journalistic coverage of local government, courts, or public affairs — precisely in the places where civic engagement most needs an informational foundation. It follows that whatever we think about the benefits of digital media, a serious account of its consequences for democracy cannot be limited to its most optimistic possibilities.',
