      text: 'What I find most interesting about the current moment in urban policy is the tension between two quite different models of how cities should be governed. On one side, we have what you might call the "smart city" model — the idea that urban problems are fundamentally technical in nature and can be addressed through better data, more efficient algorithms, and the application of technology to infrastructure management. On the other side, we have what I would call the democratic city model — the view that urban problems are fundamentally political: about whose interests are served by planning decisions, who bears the costs of urban change, and who has meaningful voice in shaping the environments they inhabit. Furthermore, these are not merely different approaches to the same problem — they are grounded in quite different theories of what the city is, what it is for, and who has the right to determine its future. The smart city model tends to treat cities as systems to be optimised; the democratic city model tends to treat them as political communities to be governed.',
