      text: "I want to suggest that the most important thing that critical linguistics teaches us is not how to identify propaganda in obviously manipulative texts — that is usually not difficult — but how to read the ideology embedded in apparently neutral, everyday language. The phrase 'taxpayers' money' is not a neutral economic description — it imports a particular conception of the state as a service provider to paying customers, excludes from view the contributions of those who don't pay income tax but contribute in other ways, and naturalises a set of assumptions about the relationship between payment and political entitlement. Similarly, when newspapers describe strikers as 'holding the country to ransom,' they import into the description a presupposition of illegitimacy that frames all subsequent debate. Not only does this linguistic choice shape how readers interpret the event — it constrains which policy responses appear legitimate and which appear extreme, in ways that systematically advantage those whose interests the dominant discourse serves. The question we should be asking of any political text is not 'Is this true or false?' but 'What can be said within this discourse, and what is made unsayable?'",
